Patch Set 5:

Hi Neale, thanks for the review.

The set / clear functions allow to use the api & cli sources as flags, which preserves the current behaviour where we can add a table several time and only need to delete it once. I think this makes it so that the comment in mpls_api.c and in the .api files remain true.

We could also use regular increment / decrement on the cli & api lock sources, but imo it would be less desirable as it would be a hidden behaviour change (without API change).

Patch Set 5:

Doesn't the inclusion of the local udp port further violate the standard?

The source port should be the source port of the inner header, should it not.  Is there a reason for polarizing all traffic between a pair of vteps?   

https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-nvo3-vxlan-gpe-11#page-15

Patch Set 5:

> The source port should be the source port of the inner header, should it not.  Is there a reason for polarizing all traffic between a pair of vteps?   
> 
> https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-nvo3-vxlan-gpe-11#page-15

Paul... I'm super sympathetic on that point... but if you look at implementations of vxlan (including GPE) in the kernel, srcport and dstport are settable, so to be able to interoperate, we need to be able to set them too.

From iproute2:

ip link add DEVICE type vxlan id VNI [ dev PHYS_DEV ] [ { group | remote } IPADDR ] [ local { IPADDR | any } ] [ ttl TTL ] [ tos TOS ] [ df DF ] [ flowlabel FLOWLABEL ] [ dstport PORT ] [ srcport MIN MAX ] [ [no]learning ] [ [no]proxy ] [ [no]rsc ] [ [no]l2miss ] [ [no]l3miss ] [ [no]udpcsum ] [ [no]udp6zerocsumtx ] [ [no]udp6zerocsumrx ] [ ageing SECONDS ] [ maxaddress NUMBER ] [ [no]external ] [ gbp ] [ gpe ]

Hi Ed,

Maybe you can clear up my confusion.  This linux implementation varies the src encapsulation port, see: [0]. 

The proposed change here treats all tunnels as pt-pt tunnels, yet even the linux docs highlight the point that vxlans are point-multipoint.("Unlike most tunnels, a VXLAN is a 1 to N network, not just point to point. A VXLAN device can learn the IP address of the other endpoint either dynamically in a manner similar to a learning bridge, or make use of statically-configured forwarding entries.") [1] 

I think we are mixing up the encapsulation srcport and the listen port.  They are separate and distinct.  

If the srcport were actually a range between min/max, as in your example in iproute2, then one would be able to use the defaults and hash based on the encapsulated packet src port, and when min == max, there would only be a single src port, but the listen port is separate and distinct, which MAY, but not MUST be the same. 

[0] https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/c4681547bcce777daf576925a966ffa824edd09d/drivers/net/vxlan.c#L2677
[1] https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/v5.8/networking/vxlan.html

What am I missing?

Paul

>2. Interfaces with /32 IP addresses intentionally assigned

ARP is useless on a link with a /32. There are, by definition, no neighbours attached.

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
> 
> >2. Interfaces with /32 IP addresses intentionally assigned
> 
> ARP is useless on a link with a /32. There are, by definition, no neighbours attached.

And yet... it was working and doing useful work for me up till the SAS changes.

When you have two /32s on either end of an ethernet interface... and you've explicitly configured a route for the /32 out that interface via that IP address... you need ARP to get the ethernet address, or you need to do insanely complex things to manually get the ip neighbor information and then configure it.

This is true for any L2 based tunnel (like VXLAN) over which you want to use /32s on the interface.

I think:

Should ARP for 1.1.1.1 on eth0. 

Technically we should have an api allowing you to arp for whatever you please. 
Eg v6 default was originally to try address resolution for the world if no default router. Ie assume everything was directly connected.

here is the VPP code that will, or at least is intended, to prevent it from replying to ARP requests from hosts that are not on the link:
  https://github.com/FDio/vpp/blob/fc1f3ef76abf08661c4b214414710a1793dceb6e/src/vnet/arp/arp.c#L501
here's the commit that brought it in:

commit ca1936123cbe2c02521dce6c7890d66135888654
Author: Neale Ranns <nranns@cisco.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 14 06:50:08 2017 -0700

the logic being that if the host is not on link, it's a clear spoof.

you don't need insanely complicated things, you need a /31. And you benefit as your system becomes less complex because you don't need the route.

It's on the link, just not within the neighbour's understanding of a covering subnet.
In Ed's case I think the configuration is symmetric, so the ARP tell-me address would match.
This discussion touches the "is VPP a standards compliant router or is VPP a framework for building arbitrary network applications". I tend to lean towards the latter, where the "business logic" / protocol compliance should go somewhere else. And VPP shouldn't limit the amount of rope we give developers of solutions.

As has been shown by IPv6 the IP subnet model does not have / need to be contained within a subnet.
ARP has no notion of subnets.

Neither do ARP have an IP source address. It has a sender's protocol field. This is purely as an optimisation, assuming that since A want to talk to B, it's likely that soon B wants to talk to A too. Ignoring unidirectional links, then it I agree that you shouldn't install a mapping for an IP address you do not have reachability to. But in the following case you do:

router A
 interface A
   ip address 1.1.1.1/32
 ip route 2.2.2.2/32 via 2.2.2.2, interface A
router B
 interface B
  ip address 2.2.2.2/32
 ip route 1.1.1.1/32 via 1.1.1.1, interface B

I can tell you definitively the peer does in fact respond to the arp with this gerrit.  I am using a link with a /32 (and /128) on each end of the link.  Prior to SAS, that worked.  With this gerrit that removes the preclusion of sending arp due to source address selection, it works again.

In a very very brief perusal of the code relate to avoiding the receiving side of the arp getting its arp cache flooded, if memory serves, it does roughly an RPF check (ie, did I expect this IP off this interface).  I think that's a good check.  It certainly is satisfied by prefixes 'covering' but that's not the only way to satisfy it.

I think that the useful approach here is to recast things from 'covering prefix on interface' to a realization that what we are really doing is enforcing:

1.  Does the fib have reason to believe we can productively send an arp out this interface.  Covering prefixes certainly provides such a reason, but its not the only cause of such entries in the fib.
2.  When receiving an arp, does the fib have reason to believe we should be should be expecting things from this IP address off this interface?  Again, covering prefixes are one great way to satisfy that... but not the only one.

in general IP networking, 1. you establish your adjacent peerings (ARP), 2. you run routing protocols, 3. you get routes. So using routing (the FIB/RIB) to determine whether to send ARPs is backwards. Static routes are not the tool to express adjacent relationships, that's what subnets are for.

true, adding a static route for each peer in a network is the equivalent to adding a subnet, and you'll know that adding these host routes is what the ip-neighbour/adjacency subsystem does on your behalf.

but, routes (at least the way you have defined them) don't express the 'connected to relationship' that ARP is interested in, they only express a 'reachable via'. There's nothing in VPP's FIB that's able to derive the connected to relationship from your route. hence ARP is having trouble.
Now if you had them like this
  ip route 1.1.1.2/32 via eth0
that would be different. This is an attached route that states that the 1.1.1.2/32 network is indeed attached to eth0 (and so is similar to if you had done 'set int ip eth0 1.1.1.2/32' - in fact you have to do it like this for extranets). but please don't consider this to be me advocating for routing this way 😊

Patch Set 1:

We can't really switch between attach modes. For instance, to disable sapi, we'd have to close all existing app attachments, close the sock api socket, potentially stop polling app rx mqs events. The first would also be needed when going from bapi to sapi.

That's why we're not exposing a configuration knob. Isn't the startup.conf option enough?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> We can't really switch between attach modes. For instance, to disable sapi, we'd have to close all existing app attachments, close the sock api socket, potentially stop polling app rx mqs events. The first would also be needed when going from bapi to sapi.
> 
> That's why we're not exposing a configuration knob. Isn't the startup.conf option enough?

Right, I was considering this as some kind of startup api - provided that the control plane ensures
it only calls it prior to depending api calls. But if it can get confusing to users we let's use the startup.conf option

likely better solution would be to detect wrong version and disable it automatically or just disable certain functionality (in this case likely it is all about disabling chacha-poly)

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> likely better solution would be to detect wrong version and disable it automatically or just disable certain functionality (in this case likely it is all about disabling chacha-poly)

The symbols not available from ipsec-mb 0.55 version are:

IMB_CIPHER_DIRECTION
ipsecmb_ops_chacha_poly
ipsecmb_ops_chacha_poly_chained

Detecting these from cmake may be tricky, particularly the ENUM. But perhaps just checking for ipsecmb_ops_chacha_poly() using Cmake's check_function_exists() would be sufficient?
Which bits of ipsecmb.c to then conditional exclude I'm less sure of, suggestion are welcome. I'm guess all functions with *chacha* with and some bits of crypto_ipsecmb_init().
